---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import BackLink from "../../components/BackLink.astro";
---

<BaseLayout>

<article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">

<BackLink href="/projects" label="Back to projects" />

<header class="mb-14">

<h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold mb-4">
Architecture Comparison — Reservation System
</h1>

<p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
A practical experiment exploring how different architectural
approaches respond to increasing domain complexity.
</p>

</header>

<section class="mb-14">

<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
Project Goal
</h2>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4">
This project is a practical laboratory designed to compare different
architectural styles applied to the same functional domain.
</p>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
The objective is not to demonstrate that one architecture is superior
to another, but to analyse how each approach behaves as business
complexity increases.
</p>

</section>

<section class="mb-14">

<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-6">
What is evaluated
</h2>

<ul class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 list-disc pl-6">

<li>Structural complexity</li>
<li>Cognitive complexity</li>
<li>Testability</li>
<li>Coupling level</li>
<li>Scalability of the design</li>
<li>Evolution capacity</li>
<li>Cost of change when adding new rules</li>

</ul>

</section>

<section class="mb-14">

<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
Common Domain
</h2>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4">
All architectures implement the same domain: a multi-product reservation
system with progressively more complex business rules.
</p>

<ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 list-disc pl-6">

<li>Products reservable by date ranges</li>
<li>Optional extras (fixed or per-night)</li>
<li>Total price calculation</li>
<li>Progressively more complex business rules</li>

</ul>

</section>

<section class="mb-16">

<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-6">
Architectures Compared
</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">

<div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6">

<h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">
A01 — Monolithic Eloquent
</h3>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm mb-2">
Pure Active Record approach using Eloquent directly.
</p>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm">
Fast to develop but tightly coupled to the framework. Complexity grows
rapidly as domain rules increase.
</p>

</div>

<div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6">

<h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">
A02 — Repository Pattern
</h3>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm mb-2">
Separation between controller, service layer and repository abstraction.
</p>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm">
Introduces dependency inversion and improves testability while keeping
a relatively simple domain model.
</p>

</div>

<div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6">

<h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">
A03 — Strategy + Polymorphism
</h3>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm mb-2">
Reservation behaviour varies depending on reservation type.
</p>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm">
Encapsulates business rules using polymorphism and strategy objects,
making the domain model more expressive.
</p>

</div>

<div class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6">

<h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">
A04 — Decorator Domain
</h3>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm mb-2">
Behaviour is composed dynamically through decorators.
</p>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm">
Applies the Open/Closed principle allowing rules and modifiers to be
added without modifying existing logic.
</p>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section class="mb-16">

<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-6">
Evolution Phases
</h2>

<div class="space-y-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">

<p>
<strong>Phase 01 — Base Calculation</strong><br/>
Base price, extras and total calculation.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Phase 02 — Conditional Rules</strong><br/>
Volume discounts, promotions and cross-rule validations.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Phase 03 — Polymorphic Behaviour</strong><br/>
Different reservation types with distinct pricing logic.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Phase 04 — Composable Rules</strong><br/>
Dynamic modifiers, chained rules and complex interactions.
</p>

</div>

</section>

<section class="mb-16">

<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-6">
Evaluation Criteria
</h2>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4">
During the experiment each architecture is evaluated based on how
the design evolves when complexity increases.
</p>

<ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 list-disc pl-6">

<li>Number of classes</li>
<li>Lines of code</li>
<li>Structural complexity</li>
<li>Ease of introducing new business rules</li>
<li>Testing difficulty</li>
<li>Clarity of the domain model</li>

</ul>

</section>

<section class="mb-14">

<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
Architectural Philosophy
</h2>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4">
Architectures are not inherently good or bad.
</p>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
They are appropriate or inappropriate depending on the domain
complexity, expected evolution and long-term maintenance cost.
</p>

</section>

<section>

<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
Purpose of the Project
</h2>

<p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
This project is intended as an educational exploration of software
design and architectural decision-making. It provides a controlled
environment to observe how different design strategies respond to
growing business complexity.
</p>

</section>

</article>

</BaseLayout>